The paper deals with the cryptographic primitive of oblivious transfer, which is a fundamental concept in cryptography and two/multi-party computation. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the category of "Cryptography and Security" (cs.CR). The paper also discusses the efficiency and computational assumptions of the protocol, which suggests that it may also belong to the categories of "Information Theory" (cs.IT) and "Computational Complexity" (cs.CC). Additionally, the paper presents new definitions and reductions, which may indicate that it belongs to the category of "Data Structures and Algorithms" (cs.DS). Finally, the paper discusses the computational setting and how weak oblivious transfer can be strengthened, which suggests that it may also belong to the category of "Machine Learning" (cs.LG).
